\fs36\cf1 Outputs Tab\plain\fs24 
\par \pard \fs20 
\par The Outputs tab controls the location and style of the \uldb output files\plain\fs20 {\v Output_Files}.
\par 
\par \{bmc bm33.BMP\}
\par \fs24 
\par \pard\li715\fi-355 \b\fs20 Output Directory for Files:\plain\fs20  selects the directory where the \uldb output files\plain\fs20 {\v Output_Files} will be saved.
\par 
\par \b Output Format:\plain\fs20  When set to Classic, this will output the standard files documented \uldb here\plain\fs20 {\v Output_Files}..If you choose Femtosoft Compatible, the files will be written in the same format as the \uldb expected input format\plain\fs20 {\v HEADER}, including headers.  This way, you can read in the data from previous runs and use that as input to the FROG algorithm.  Remember, the FROG output format is in constant frequency, so that on the \uldb experimental data tab\plain\fs20 {\v Experimental_Data_Tab} you'll need to select Order:Delay and Read In As: Constant Frequency (the opposite of most experimental setups).  The output format selection that you make here is persisted, so that you won't need to set it every time you run the program.
\par \pard\li715\fi-355 \fs24 
\par \b\fs20 Phase Blanking Level:\plain\fs20  this unit sets the level at which the phase is set to zero. in the electric fields and spectra \uldb output files\plain\fs20 {\v Output_Files}.  Especially for experimental data, the wings of the retrieved pulse are just noise.  Because the real and imaginary parts of the field are varying independently, the phase in the wings of the field fluctuates wildly.  This can be extremely distracting when plotting the pulse.  If phase blanking is set at 0.0001, for example, then the phase is set to zero for all points where the intensity is less than 0.0001 of the peak intensity.  This affects only the phase in the \uldb output file\plain\fs20 {\v Output_Files}; the real and imaginary components are still output unchanged.
\par \pard\li715\fi-355 
\par \b Display Graphics:\plain\fs20  when this box is check the FROG algorithm will update the \uldb FROG trace\plain\fs20 {\v FROG_Trace_Windows} and \uldb Electric Field and Spectrum windows\plain\fs20 {\v Electric_Field_and_Spectrum_Windows} as the algorithm runs.  Updating the graphics slows the algorithm down significantly, so uncheck this box for faster pulse retrieval.  Unexpectedly, the speedup gained becomes smaller as the \uldb grid size\plain\fs20 {\v Grid_Size} becomes larger.  This is because for larger grids, a larger portion of each iteration of the algorithm is spent on the actual numerics of the pulse retrieval, rather than on the display update.
\par \pard\li715\fi-355 
\par \b Always Overwrite Results:\plain\fs20  When this is checked, FROG will write its results into the selected directory, and silently overwrite any previous runs' files there.  This is useful if you are running a lot of theoretical traces that you are not going to save.  When this item is unchecked, if there are previous data files in the directory a dialog box will appear to warn you.  At this point you can elect to overwrite, cancel the save, or save to a different directory.  With important experimental data files, the recommended usage is to put each data file in its own directory, along with the FROG output files.\fs24 
