\fs36\cf1 XFROG Algorithm\plain\fs24 
\par \pard 
\par \fs20 The operation of the XFROG algorithm is very similar to that of the FROG algorithm.  There are a few notable differences:
\par \fs24 
\par \pard\li715\fi-355 \b\fs20 Two sets of calibrations\plain\fs20  - the calibrations for both the test and reference pulse must be entered.  The XFROG algorithm presents two windows for this purpose.\fs24 
\par \fs20 
\par \b New Set of Nonlinearities\plain\fs20  - While the 3rd-order nonlinearities are relatively unchanged, the set of second-order nonlinearities is changed.  Second-harmonic generation is now more aptly named sum-frequency generation.  And there are two more parametric downconversion processed, named Difference Frequency Generation (1 and 2).
\par \pard\li715\fi-355 
\par \b Reduced Set of Strategies\plain\fs20  - Currently only the basic FROG, the expo, and the XFROG projections \uldb strategies\plain\fs20 {\v Strategies_Tab} are available.  \uldb Shortcuts\plain\fs20 {\v 1752HXP} are available in the XFROG projection algorithm.
\par 
\par \fs24 
\par \pard \b\fs28 Algorithm Description\plain\fs24 
\par 
\par \pard\li715\fi-355 \uldb \fs20 Test Field Calibrations\plain\fs20 {\v Test_Calibration_Window} - sets the algorithm parameters, and the source of the test field or original XFROG trace.
\par 
\par \uldb Reference Field Calibrations\plain\fs20 {\v Reference_Field_Calibrations} - determines the source of the reference field.
\par 
\par \uldb Algorithm Windows\plain\fs20 {\v FROG_Pulse_Retrieval_Windows} - the same set of algorithm windows seen in the FROG algorithm are used in XFROG.\fs24 
\par \page
{\up $}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up $} XFROG Nonlinearities}
{\up #}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up #} XFROG_Nonlinearities}
\pard\keepn {\up K}{\footnote\pard\plain{\up K} DFG;SFG;XFROG Nonlinearities}
\fs36\cf1 XFROG Nonlinearities\plain\fs24 
\par \pard \fs20 
\par In XFROG, a well-characterized reference pulse is used to measure a weak unknown pulse.  We call the pulse to be measured the test pulse, indicated by the subscript \i t\plain\fs20 , while the reference pulse is indicated by the subscript \i r\plain\fs20 .
\par 
\par The nonlinearities in XFROG are slightly different from \uldb FROG nonlinearities\plain\fs20 {\v Optical_Nonlinearity}, including some nonlinear interactions that are not available in FROG.
\par \fs24 
\par \b\fs28 Nonlinear Optical Interactions\plain\fs24 
\par \fs20 
\par There are four possible types of nonlinear interactions, three third order and one second order. \fs24 
\par \pard\sb115 \b\fs20 Third order interactions\plain\fs24 
\par \pard 
\par \pard\li715\fi-355 \ul\fs20 PG\plain\fs20  (Polarization Gate) - commonly generated by Kerr-effect-induced polarization rotation in an isotropic medium.  Can also be generated by so-called "transient-gate" FROG (using a BOXCARS-type phase-matching geometry) or by a cascaded second-order interaction.
\par \fs24 
\par \pard\qc \f4\fs20 \{bmc bm52.WMF\}\f2\fs24 
\par \pard\li715\fi-355 \fs20 
\par \ul SD\plain\fs20  (Self-Diffraction) - generated by a three-wave mixing geometry (two input beams write a grating in the material, and one of the beams scatters off this grating to produce the [third] output beam).  Can also be generated in a transient-grating geometry or cascaded second-order interactions.
\par \fs24 
\par \pard\qc \f4\fs20 \{bmc bm53.WMF\}\f2\fs24 
\par \pard\li715\fi-355 \fs20 
\par \ul THG\plain\fs20  (Third-Harmonic Generation) - uses a two-input-beam geometry where the signal beam is the third harmonic of the input beam.  Can also be generated by cascaded second-order interactions.\fs24 
\par \pard 
\par \pard\qc \f4\fs20 \{bmc bm54.WMF\}\f2\fs24 
\par \pard 
\par \pard\sb115 \b\fs20 Second order interactions\plain\fs24 
\par \pard 
\par \pard\li715\fi-355 \ul\fs20 SFG\plain\fs20  (Sum Frequency Generation) - uses a standard autocorrelation geometry in a frequency-doubling crystal, where the two beams mix together to form the sum frequency.\fs24 
\par \pard 
\par \pard\qc \f4\fs20 \{bmc bm55.WMF\}\f2\fs24 
\par \pard 
\par \pard\li715\fi-355 \ul\fs20 DFG1\plain\fs20  (Difference Frequency Generation Type 1) - Uses a parametric downconversion process to find the difference frequency between the two beams.  In type 1 DFG, the test field is a higher frequency than the reference.\fs24 
\par \pard 
\par \pard\qc \f4\fs20 \{bmc bm56.WMF\}\f2\fs24 
\par \pard 
\par \pard\li715\fi-355 \ul\fs20 DFG2\plain\fs20  (Difference Frequency Generation Type 2) - Same as DFG1, but the reference field is a higher frequency than the test field.\fs24 
\par \pard 
\par \pard\qc \f4\fs20 \{bmc bm57.WMF\}\f2\fs24 
